{"title_page": "Yacouba Sawadogo", "text_new": "[[File:Zai in Batodi.webm|thumb|Za\u00ef, Batodi, Taja\u00e9, Nigeria (June 2012).]]\n'''Yacouba Sawadogo''' is a farmer from [[Burkina Faso]] who has been successfully using a traditional farming technique called [[Za\u00ef]] to restore soils damaged by [[desertification]] and [[drought]]. Such techniques are known by the collective terms [[agroforestry]] and [[farmer-managed natural regeneration]].<ref name=\"Hertsgaard\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/regreening-africa/|title=Regreening Africa|last=Hertsgaard|first=Mark|magazine=[[The Nation]]|date=19 November 2009|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nA 2010 documentary feature film ''The Man Who Stopped the Desert,'' first screened in the UK, portrays his life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.1080films.co.uk/project-mwsd.htm |title=The Man Who Stopped the Desert |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208035816/http://www.1080films.co.uk/project-mwsd.htm |archive-date=8 February 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe is a native speaker of [[Mossi language|Mossi]].<ref name=\"Hertsgaard\" /> In 2018, he was awarded the [[Right Livelihood Award]].<ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/environment/sustainability/blessed-tree-regeneration-pioneer-tony-rinaudo-gets-global-gong-20180924-p505mi.html 'Blessed': Tree regeneration pioneer Tony Rinaudo gets global gong], Peter Hannam, [[Sydney Morning Herald]], 24 September 2018</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSawadogo was sent to a religious school where the students often didn't have enough to eat. Being the smallest and youngest, he was the one who had to go without.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Background==\n{{Further|Sahel drought}}\n\nThe northern portions of Burkina Faso fall in the [[Sahel|Sahel Belt]], a semi-arid region between the [[Sahara Desert]] to the north and tropical savannahs further south. The region periodically suffers from drought. The most recent major drought occurred from 1972 to 1984, resulting in a famine which killed hundreds of thousands of people.<ref name=\"Hertsgaard\" />\n\nOne effect of the drought was widespread [[desertification]]. Combined with other factors such as [[overgrazing]], poor land management, and overpopulation, the drought led to a substantial increase in barren land, particularly on slopes, due to the comparative difficulty of cultivating sloping land.<ref name=\"kabore\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ifpri.org/publication/emergence-and-spreading-improved-traditional-soil-and-water-conservation-practice-burkin |title=The emergence and spreading of an improved traditional soil and water conservation practice in Burkina Faso |last1=Kabor\u00e9 |first1=Daniel |last2=Reij |first2=Chris |year=2004 |publisher=International Food Policy Research Institute |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130108085325/http://www.ifpri.org/publication/emergence-and-spreading-improved-traditional-soil-and-water-conservation-practice-burkin |archive-date=8 January 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Uncultivated, the soil experienced increased [[erosion]] and [[soil compaction|compaction]]. Such practices also led to an annual one metre reduction in the [[water table]] in the 1980s.<ref name=\"Hertsgaard\" />\n\n==Soil rehabilitation==\nTogether with Mathieu Ou\u00e9draogo, another local farm innovator, Yacouba Sawadogo began experimenting with techniques for rehabilitating damaged soil in the 1970s.<ref name=\"Whiting\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-burkina-landrights-hunger/they-will-destroy-my-fathers-grave-says-farmer-who-turned-back-the-desert-idUSKCN11W1Y6|title='They will destroy my father's grave,' says farmer who turned back the desert|last=Whiting|first=Alex|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=26 September 2016|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> He relies on simple approaches traditional to the region: cordons pierreux and [[za\u00ef]] holes. Both Sawadogo and Ou\u00e9draogo have engaged in extension and outreach efforts to spread their techniques throughout the region.\n\n===Cordons pierreux===\nCordons pierreux are thin lines of fist-sized stones laid across fields. Their purpose is to form a catchment. When rain falls, it pushes silt across the surface of the field, which then fetches up against the cordon. Slowing down the flow of water gives it more time to soak into the earth. The accumulated silt also provides a comparatively fertile spot for seeds of local plants to sprout. The plants slow the water even further in turn, and their roots break up the compacted soil, thereby making it easier for more water to soak in.<ref name=\"mann\">{{cite web |url=http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2008/09/soil/mann-text |title=Our Good Earth |last=Mann |first=Charles C. |year=2008 |publisher=National Geographic |access-date=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Za\u00ef holes===\n{{Main|Za\u00ef}}\nZa\u00ef holes also catch water, but take a slightly different approach. They are holes dug in the soil. Traditionally they were used in a limited way to restore barren land. Yacouba Sawadogo introduced the innovation of filling them with manure and other biodegradable waste, in order to provide a source of nutrients for plant life. The manure attracts termites, whose tunnels help break up the soil further. He also increased the size of the holes slightly over the traditional models.<ref name=\"kabore\"/> Za\u00ef holes have been used to help cultivate trees, sorghum, and millet.\n\nFrom the mid-1980s until 2009, the use of za\u00ef has also led to the water table levels rising by about {{convert|5|m|ft}} on average, and as much as {{convert|17|m|ft}} in some areas.<ref name=\"Hertsgaard\" />\n\n===Outreach===\nTo promote these methods, particularly za\u00ef holes, Yacouba Sawadogo holds bi-yearly \"Market Days\" at his farm in the village of Gourga. Attendees from over a hundred regional villages come to share seed samples, swap tips, and learn from one another.<ref name=\"IKNotes\">Indigenous Knowledge Notes #77, The World Bank, February 2005. http://www.worldbank.org/afr/ik/iknt77.htm(last accessed 15 September 2008) {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922235647/http://www.worldbank.org/afr/ik/iknt77.htm |date=22 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Conflict with Burkinab\u00e9 government==\nOver a period of more than two decades, Yacouba Sawadogo's work with za\u00ef holes allowed him to create a forested area of {{convert|62|acres|m2}}<ref name=\"Whiting\" /> Recently this area was annexed by the nearby city of [[Ouahigouya]], under the auspices of a government program to increase city revenues.<ref name=\"mann\"/> Under the provisions of the program, Yacouba Sawadogo and his immediate family members are each entitled to one tenth of 1 acre (400m{{sup|2}}) out of the plot, and do not receive any other compensation.\n\nSawadogo is attempting to raise US$20,000 to purchase the land.<ref name=\"leonard\">{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2008/09/11/helping_sawadogo |title=How to help Yacouba Sawadogo |last=Leonard |first=Andrew |date=11 September 2008 |website=Salon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150308141934/http://www.salon.com/2008/09/11/helping_sawadogo |archive-date=8 March 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSawadogo is now attempting to raise \u20ac100,000 because land is now valued at \u20ac100,000 from his increased work to fertilizing the lands.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.1080films.co.uk/yacoubamovie/news.htm |title=The Man Who Stopped The Desert |access-date=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2010 Sahel famine]]\n* [[Permaculture]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sawadogo, Yacouba}}\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 farmers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People involved with desert greening]]\n[[Category:Permaculturalists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Right Livelihood Award laureates]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Zai in Batodi.webm|thumb|Za\u00ef, Batodi, Taja\u00e9, Nigeria (June 2012). ]]\n'''Yacouba Sawadogo''' is a farmer from [[Burkina Faso]] who has been successfully using a traditional farming technique called [[Za\u00ef]] to restore soils damaged by [[desertification]] and [[drought]]. Such techniques are known by the collective terms [[agroforestry]] and [[farmer-managed natural regeneration]].<ref name=\"Hertsgaard\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/regreening-africa/|title=Regreening Africa|last=Hertsgaard|first=Mark|magazine=[[The Nation]]|date=19 November 2009|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nA 2010 documentary feature film ''The Man Who Stopped the Desert,'' first screened in the UK, portrays his life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.1080films.co.uk/project-mwsd.htm |title=The Man Who Stopped the Desert |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208035816/http://www.1080films.co.uk/project-mwsd.htm |archive-date=8 February 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe is a native speaker of [[Mossi language|Mossi]].<ref name=\"Hertsgaard\" /> In 2018, he was awarded the [[Right Livelihood Award]].<ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/environment/sustainability/blessed-tree-regeneration-pioneer-tony-rinaudo-gets-global-gong-20180924-p505mi.html 'Blessed': Tree regeneration pioneer Tony Rinaudo gets global gong], Peter Hannam, [[Sydney Morning Herald]], 24 September 2018</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSawadogo was sent to a religious school where the students often didn't have enough to eat. Being the smallest and youngest, he was the one who had to go without.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Background==\n{{Further information|Sahel drought}}\n\nThe northern portions of Burkina Faso fall in the [[Sahel|Sahel Belt]], a semi-arid region between the [[Sahara Desert]] to the north and tropical savannahs further south. The region periodically suffers from drought. The most recent major drought occurred from 1972 to 1984, resulting in a famine which killed hundreds of thousands of people.<ref name=\"Hertsgaard\" />\n\nOne effect of the drought was widespread [[desertification]]. Combined with other factors such as [[overgrazing]], poor land management, and overpopulation, the drought led to a substantial increase in barren land, particularly on slopes, due to the comparative difficulty of cultivating sloping land.<ref name=\"kabore\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ifpri.org/publication/emergence-and-spreading-improved-traditional-soil-and-water-conservation-practice-burkin |title=The emergence and spreading of an improved traditional soil and water conservation practice in Burkina Faso |last1=Kabor\u00e9 |first1=Daniel |last2=Reij |first2=Chris |year=2004 |publisher=International Food Policy Research Institute |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130108085325/http://www.ifpri.org/publication/emergence-and-spreading-improved-traditional-soil-and-water-conservation-practice-burkin |archive-date=8 January 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Uncultivated, the soil experienced increased [[erosion]] and [[soil compaction|compaction]]. Such practices also led to an annual one metre reduction in the [[water table]] in the 1980s.<ref name=\"Hertsgaard\" />\n\n==Soil rehabilitation==\nTogether with Mathieu Ou\u00e9draogo, another local farm innovator, Yacouba Sawadogo began experimenting with techniques for rehabilitating damaged soil in the 1970s.<ref name=\"Whiting\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-burkina-landrights-hunger/they-will-destroy-my-fathers-grave-says-farmer-who-turned-back-the-desert-idUSKCN11W1Y6|title='They will destroy my father's grave,' says farmer who turned back the desert|last=Whiting|first=Alex|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=26 September 2016|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> He relies on simple approaches traditional to the region: cordons pierreux and [[za\u00ef]] holes. Both Sawadogo and Ou\u00e9draogo have engaged in extension and outreach efforts to spread their techniques throughout the region.\n\n===Cordons pierreux===\nCordons pierreux are thin lines of fist-sized stones laid across fields. Their purpose is to form a catchment. When rain falls, it pushes silt across the surface of the field, which then fetches up against the cordon. Slowing down the flow of water gives it more time to soak into the earth. The accumulated silt also provides a comparatively fertile spot for seeds of local plants to sprout. The plants slow the water even further in turn, and their roots break up the compacted soil, thereby making it easier for more water to soak in.<ref name=\"mann\">{{cite web |url=http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2008/09/soil/mann-text |title=Our Good Earth |last=Mann |first=Charles C. |year=2008 |publisher=National Geographic |access-date=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Za\u00ef holes===\n{{Main article|Za\u00ef}}\nZa\u00ef holes also catch water, but take a slightly different approach. They are holes dug in the soil. Traditionally they were used in a limited way to restore barren land. Yacouba Sawadogo introduced the innovation of filling them with manure and other biodegradable waste, in order to provide a source of nutrients for plant life. The manure attracts termites, whose tunnels help break up the soil further. He also increased the size of the holes slightly over the traditional models.<ref name=\"kabore\"/> Za\u00ef holes have been used to help cultivate trees, sorghum, and millet.\n\nFrom the mid-1980s until 2009, the use of za\u00ef has also led to the water table levels rising by about {{convert|5|m|ft}} on average, and as much as {{convert|17|m|ft}} in some areas.<ref name=\"Hertsgaard\" />\n\n===Outreach===\nTo promote these methods, particularly za\u00ef holes, Yacouba Sawadogo holds bi-yearly \"Market Days\" at his farm in the village of Gourga. Attendees from over a hundred regional villages come to share seed samples, swap tips, and learn from one another.<ref name=\"IKNotes\">Indigenous Knowledge Notes #77, The World Bank, February 2005. http://www.worldbank.org/afr/ik/iknt77.htm(last accessed 15 September 2008) {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922235647/http://www.worldbank.org/afr/ik/iknt77.htm |date=22 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Conflict with Burkinab\u00e9 government==\nOver a period of more than two decades, Yacouba Sawadogo's work with za\u00ef holes allowed him to create a forested area of {{convert|62|acres|m2}}<ref name=\"Whiting\" /> Recently this area was annexed by the nearby city of [[Ouahigouya]], under the auspices of a government program to increase city revenues.<ref name=\"mann\"/> Under the provisions of the program, Yacouba Sawadogo and his immediate family members are each entitled to one tenth of 1 acre (400m{{sup|2}}) out of the plot, and do not receive any other compensation.\n\nSawadogo is attempting to raise US$20,000 to purchase the land.<ref name=\"leonard\">{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2008/09/11/helping_sawadogo |title=How to help Yacouba Sawadogo |last=Leonard |first=Andrew |date=11 September 2008 |website=Salon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150308141934/http://www.salon.com/2008/09/11/helping_sawadogo |archive-date=8 March 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSawadogo is now attempting to raise \u20ac100,000 because land is now valued at \u20ac100,000 from his increased work to fertilizing the lands.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.1080films.co.uk/yacoubamovie/news.htm |title=The Man Who Stopped The Desert |access-date=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2010 Sahel famine]]\n* [[Permaculture]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sawadogo, Yacouba}}\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 farmers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People involved with desert greening]]\n[[Category:Permaculturalists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Right Livelihood Award laureates]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yacouba_Sawadogo"}
